===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|spadu|lang=ang}}, {{term|spada|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*spadō}}. Cognate with [[Old Frisian]] {{term|spada|lang=ofs}}, [[Old Saxon]] {{term|spado|lang=osx}}, German {{term|Spaten|lang=de}}. Ultimately from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*sph₂-dʰ-}}, whence also Ancient Greek {{term|σπάθη||blade|tr=spathē|lang=grc}}, Hittite {{term||išpatar|spear}} {{rfscript|und|sc=Xsux}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A [[garden]] [[tool]] with a handle and a flat [[blade]] for [[dig]]ging. Not to be confused with a [[shovel]] which is used for moving earth or other materials.
#* '''1898''', {{w|J. Meade Falkner}}, [[w:Moonfleet|Moonfleet]] Chapter 4
#*: 'Make your mind easy,' Ratsey said; 'I have dug too often in this graveyard for any to wonder if they see me with a '''spade'''.'
# A [[playing card]] marked with the symbol {{term|♠}}.
#: ''I've got only one '''spade''' in my hand.''
# {{context|offensive|ethnic slur|lang=en}} A [[black]] person.
# A cutting instrument used in [[flense|flensing]] a [[whale]].

